1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 c5 {The Benoni approach against Petrosian
system is much less popular than bishop's moves, but has still been played
many times by strong Grandmasters.} 5. d5 {Here, Black has two major
continuations:} exd5 {Not surprisingly, this is a more popular move} ({than} 
5... Ba6 {Here, I prefer the pawn sacrifice to speed up development:} 6. Nc3
Bxc4 7. e4 Bxf1 {Black had no reasonable alternatives,} ({since} 7... exd5 {
runs into} 8. Bxc4 (8. e5 {is also strong}) 8... dxc4 9. e5 Ng8 10. O-O Nc6 11.
Ne4 $1 {when Black would have a very difficult time to complete his kingside
development.}) 8. Rxf1 {For the pawn, White obtained a considerable space
advantage, which seriously hinders opponent's development.} d6 ({In case of} 
8... b5 {I would like to suggest a new interesting idea} 9. g4 $5 $146 {
with the following point:} Nxg4 10. Nxb5 Qa5+ 11. Nc3 Nf6 12. Qe2 $1 Be7 13.
Rg1 {with a promising initiative.}) ({Game Sherwin-Stefansson, Kallithea 2002,
saw} 8... Qc8 9. Bg5 Qb7 {which is hardly a good idea for Black as he
seriously lags in development. After:} 10. Qe2 Be7 11. O-O-O h6 12. Bxf6 $146
Bxf6 13. e5 {would secure white edge.}) 9. e5 $1 {This direct move is more
critical} ({than} 9. dxe6 fxe6 10. e5 dxe5 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Nxe5 Kc8 {
which occurred in two Grandmaster games. There is no doubt that White has a
clear compensation, but the black position is defensible.}) 9... dxe5 10. Qa4+ {
A logical follow-up to White's 9th move.} Qd7 ({Even though it looks very
passive, it was objectively better to defend with} 10... Nbd7 {After:} 11. Bg5
a6 12. dxe6 fxe6 13. O-O-O b5 14. Qh4 $1 Qb6 15. Rfe1 $36 {White has a very
powerful initiative for two sacrificed pawns.}) 11. Nb5 $1 {Now we see the
point of 9.e5 - the e5-pawn is hanging with a tempo. Black is already in
serious trouble and it is not surprising that the game ended very quickly after
} Kd8 12. Nxe5 Qe8 13. dxe6 Qxe6 14. Bf4 Nbd7 15. O-O-O Rc8 16. Nxa7 {Lubbe,N 
(2496)-Vanheirzeele, D (2089) Lueneburg 2015}) 6. cxd5 g6 ({The alternative is
to develop bishop to e7} 6... d6 7. e4 Be7 {although this is obviously an
inferior way to develop the bishop.} 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Be2 {This is supposed to be
a very favourable version of Benoni structure for White because it is difficult
for Black to create counterplay on any side of the board. The queenside
expansion plan with a6 and b5 can be easily neutralized, while there is hardly
any pressure on e4-pawn in the centre. White should have no problem to apply
positional pressure with standard manoeuvres such as Nd2-c4, etc.} a6 10. a4 Re8
11. O-O Nbd7 12. Nd2 Bf8 {This was played in Berg, K (2420)-Dabrowska, K (2305)
Cappelle-la-Grande 1995 and now I like} 13. f3 $146 g6 14. Nc4 Ne5 15. Na3 {
when White is comfortably better in the view of Be3, Qd2 and f4 at the right
moment.}) 7. Nc3 Bg7 ({In case of} 7... d6 8. e4 Bg7 {White has an extra
option to include} 9. Bb5+ $5 Bd7 ({Clearly worse is} 9... Nbd7 10. Bf4 Qe7 11.
Bc6 $1 {when white bishops run rampant.} Rb8 12. O-O Nh5 13. Bg5 Bf6 14. Bh6
Bg7 15. Bg5 Bf6 16. Bh6 Bg7 17. Bxg7 Nxg7 18. e5 $36 {and White developed a
powerful initiative in Rajkovic, D (2490)-De Firmian, N Smederevska Palanka 1981}
) 10. a4 O-O 11. O-O a6 {This was played in Hernando Rodrigo, J (2336)
-Marchador Villalba, J (2039) Barcelona 2012. Black would not mind the trade on
d7 to spped up his development and obtain some more space for his pieces, so
White should have played} 12. Be2 $146 {when Black can still force the
exchange of light-squared bishop with} Bg4 {but this time White can do it on
his own terms:} 13. Nd2 Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Nbd7 15. Nc4 {with a better game.}) 8. e4
O-O 9. Bd3 {This is the most active square for the bishop, so there is no
reason not to develop it here.} d6 10. h3 {it is essential to prevent Bg4-move
because Black would get to trade otherwise passive bishop and obtain excellent
control of important e5-square after the exchange on f3. A similar position
often arises from Benoni move order, but without the Queen's indian move b6,
which is pretty useless for Black in these structures.} Ba6 {This is the only
way to justify the b6 move.} ({Another direction is} 10... Na6 11. O-O Nc7 12.
Re1 Re8 13. a4 a6 14. Bf4 $14 {which has occured in two games. White has a
pleasant advantage as the pressure on chronically weak d6-pawn seriously
limits Black's active options.}) 11. O-O Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nbd7 13. Bf4 {As
mentioned in comments in 10...Na6 line, White can claim a pleasant edge when
he manages to put pressure on d6-pawn like this. He just needs to make sure to
contain Black's b5 and c4 breaks, which should not be too difficult with such
good centralization. We have two examples below:} Qe7 (13... Ne8 14. Rfe1 a6
15. a4 $14 {1/2-1/2 (31) Stohl,I (2545)-Hertneck,G (2555) Austria 1994}) 14.
Bh2 Rfc8 {and now the standard knight manoeuvre:} 15. Nd2 Ne8 16. Nc4 $14 {
allows White to maintain better chances, as in Piket, J (2630)-Hertneck, G (2572)
Germany 2002} *

