{[%evp 0,27,25,23,25,-10,-7,4,20,18,46,38,50,41,47,43,36,49,41,23,22,22,25,29,
10,22,38,29,37,40]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 Ne4 {To my
great surprise, this line is quite popular nowadays. It seems unprincipled to
play twice with the same piece so early in the opening.} 6. Nxe4 Bxe4 {White
has two good options at this point. After some reflection, I opted for} 7. e3 {
7. Nd2 is a very respectable alternative.} Be7 {This is the most natural and
popular continuation. I also examined the following alternatives:} ({Firstly,
there is} 7... Qf6 {Even though it has been played by strong Grandmasters, it
seems quite artificial to me. After:} 8. Be2 Bd6 (8... d5 $6 {which happened
in Lafuente, P (2524)-Granda Zuniga, J (2647) Sao Paulo 2009, already looks
quite dubious. White could easily exploit the weakening of a4-e8 diagonal with
aggressive:} 9. Ne5 $1 $146 Bd6 10. f3 Bg6 11. Qa4+ Kf8 12. f4 $16 {with a
clear edge.}) 9. O-O O-O 10. b4 {White takes space on the queenside while also
preparing to develop the bishop to b2. Meanwhile, Black's development is quite
awkward.} c5 11. Nd2 Bc6 ({It would have probably been better to retreat to} 
11... Bb7 {although Black understandably avoided} 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. Rb1 {
In this case, White is better after} Bc6 14. Bb2 $14) 12. b5 $1 {Thanks to this
move, the knight on b8 will have an even harder time to get into the game.} Bb7
13. Bb2 cxd4 {This was played in Korobov, A (2652)-Rapport, R (2707) Riadh 2017.
White should have continued} 14. Bxd4 $146 Be5 15. Bxe5 Qxe5 16. a4 d6 17. a5
$16 {with a nice positional advantage.}) ({Secondly, in case of} 7... Bb7 {
which was met in Sundararajan, K (2513)-Duda, J (2663) Doha 2015, I would
suggest the following improvement} 8. b4 $146 Be7 9. Bb2 O-O 10. Bd3 $14 {
with a pleasant space advantage for White.}) 8. Bd3 Bb7 {Black preserves his
queen's bishop. This will be our main continuation. He has two obvious
alternatives.} ({The simplest option is} 8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 {and now Black has
two basic approaches - to play with the pawn on d6 or d5.} O-O ({The second
approach is:} 9... d5 10. O-O O-O 11. cxd5 exd5 12. b4 {I feel like this pawn
structure always promises White a slightly better game because Black has
weakened his queenside structure with the move b6, so there will always be a
backward pawn on c7 or c6. Similar positions often arise from some variations
of Nimzo Indian.} Nd7 {Now instead of 13. Bb2, I believe that white bishop
would be placed better on} 13. Bd2 $146 {preparing a4-a5 or b5 push.} a6 ({or} 
13... Bd6 14. Rfc1) 14. a4 Bd6 15. Rfc1 Qe7 16. a5 $14 {and White enjoys a
slight, but pleasant advantage due to queenside pressure.}) 10. O-O d6 (10...
f5 $6 {is hardly a good idea in the view of} 11. e4 fxe4 12. Qxe4 Nc6 {This
occured in two games. I believe that White should have played} 13. d5 $1 $146 {
with the following point:} exd5 14. cxd5 Na5 15. d6 $1 {The point of this
strong move is to deflect black bishop to be able to attack with Ng5.} cxd6 {
This is forced} ({because} 15... Bxd6 {loses to} 16. Ng5 g6 17. Qd5+ Kg7 18. b4
) 16. b4 Nc6 17. Ng5 $1 Bxg5 18. Qd5+ {and White is about to regain sacrificed
material, with a big positional advantage.}) 11. e4 Nd7 12. b4 {Black position
is very solid, however, White's space advantage should count for a small edge,
at least. Here are two model examples:} a5 (12... c5 13. bxc5 bxc5 14. d5 {
leads to a favourable pawn structure for White because d6 pawn is a long-term
liability.} Rb8 {This was played in Riazantsev, A (2608)-Asik, J (2305) Dubai
2005 and now} 15. Bf4 $146 {was strong for White} exd5 ({provoking} 15... e5
16. Bd2 $16 {when he would have a great version of a structure that often
arises from King's Indian or similar defences.}) 16. exd5 Re8 17. h3 {This is
another pawn structure in which White has a slight, but durable advantage
because of long-term pressure on d6-pawn.}) 13. Bb2 Qc8 {Black is preparing
to 'fianchetto' his queen.} 14. Rfe1 Re8 15. h3 {White can just patiently
improve his position because his position is very safe and Black still has no
clear weaknesses. However, Black's problem is that he is quite passive.} Qb7
16. d5 {White finally found a weakness in black position - c6 square. He
prepares to exploit it with Nd4-c6 manoeuvre. After} Bf6 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 18. Nd4
$14 {White enjoyed a pleasant edge in Ragger, M (2651)-Lysyj, I (2686) Wroclaw 2014
}) (8... d5 {is an interesting approach and here White should not exchange on
e4, but rather complete his development with:} 9. O-O O-O 10. b4 Nd7 11. Bb2 f5
{This was played in Sokolov, I (2650)-Riazantsev, A (2692) Dubai 2014. I believe
that now} 12. Be2 $1 $146 {would be a very nice idea, highlighting the misplaced
position of black light-squared bishop.}) 9. e4 d6 10. O-O {White established
a strong pawn centre, which should give him an edge in all cases.} O-O ({
The alternative} 10... Nd7 11. b4 c5 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. Rb1 Qc7 14. d5 {leads
to a pawn structure that was analyzed previously, only without light-squared
bishops on the board. This looks like an even better version for White.} O-O {
Now, in Kekelidze, M (2443)-Charkhalashvili, I (2323) Tbilisi 2007, White should
have played} 15. Bd2 $146 Rfb8 16. Qa4 $14 {with advantage.}) 11. Re1 Nd7 12.
b4 {As in most variations that we have seen previously, this is the preferred
way to complete development. White takes space on the queenside and prepares
Bb2. His position is harmonious and flexible. Black's setup is without any
obvious weaknesses, but it is also rather passive, so White should be happy
with opening results in the line.} c5 {occured in Quek, B (1573)-Alwan, A
Cammeray 2018 and here after the simple:} 13. bxc5 $146 bxc5 14. d5 {we
achieve a favourable pawn structure, where White maintains a slight, but
long-lasting advantage.} *

