{[%evp 0,27,19,25,23,8,0,4,13,20,38,41,61,48,14,5,85,65,44,6,76,68,86,0,18,19,
15,22,64,12]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 g6 {This
interesting option has been a choice of many strong Grandmasters. It is
considered to be a very double-edged variation that gives Black chances to
play for a win.} (5... Be7 {is a bit inaccurate because it allows White to
easily secure advantage in the centre with} 6. d5 {followed by e2-e4. Here,
one can notice the importance of Petrosian's a3 - Black can not fight for
central squares e4 and d5 by pinning him with ...Bb4.} O-O 7. e4 d6 ({The main
alternative is} 7... exd5 8. cxd5 Re8 9. Bd3 c6 {looking to undermine white
pawn centre, but White is clearly better after} 10. O-O d6 ({Another typical
central pawn structure is:} 10... cxd5 11. exd5 d6 12. Bf4 {when White has a
big space advantage.} Nbd7 13. Bb5 a6 14. Bc6 Qc7 15. Nd4 $16 {Hansen,
J-Woodhouse,S (1677) ICCF email 2015}) 11. Bf4 Nbd7 12. dxc6 Bxc6 13. Nd4 Bb7
14. Nf5 $16 {and White was clearly better in Voloshin, L (2427)-Trhal, T (2125)
Pardubice 2012}) 8. Bd3 c6 {Tension in the centre has reached the boiling
point. White can resolve it in several ways, and I suggest the following one:}
9. dxe6 $1 fxe6 10. e5 {This is the point behind White's previous move. Black
pawn structure in the centre will be compromised.} dxe5 11. Qc2 $1 {This is
the most precise follow-up. White has a nice initiative.} Nbd7 $2 12. Ng5 {
Black's last move was a big mistake and White already wins material.} e4 13.
Ncxe4 Ne5 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Bxh7+ Kh8 {Mamulaishvili,T (1788)-Toelly,M (1973)
Batumi 2014. Here, natural} 16. h4 $146 {would secure a large advantage.}) 6.
Qc2 {White's most popular move, and for a good reason - he prepares to seize
the centre with 7.e4. Black has many playable responses.} c5 {I found this
move to be the most interesting. Other possibilities are:} (6... Bg7 {This is
a rather basic approach. Black does not intervene in the centre, but hopes to
build a flexible, if somewhat passive, position.} 7. e4 O-O (7... d6 8. Bd3 O-O
{is just a transposition.}) 8. Bd3 d6 9. O-O Nbd7 {White has a wide choice
here, but I strongly prefer:} 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bd2 {After provoking a slight
weakness in black pawn structure, the bishop returns. The position in the
centre has not clarified yet, but Black is running out of useful moves. In
practice, two moves were tried:} a6 ({and} 11... e5 {which occurred in
Javakhishvili, L (2457)-Matnadze, A (2413) Mulhouse 2017. Now the natural} 12. d5
$146 {gives White a favourable version of KID pawn structure due to the misplaced
position of black light-squared bishop. White can simply continue to expand on
the queenside with b2-b4 and preparing the c4-c5 break while keeping Black's
f5 break under control. In such positions, another useful idea for White is
g3!?, Nh4, which proves the importance of provoking weakening with h7-h6 as it
becomes very difficult for Black to execute his main idea with the f5 break.}) 12.
h3 c5 {This is another typical reaction in the centre and White's response is
not different - he closes the centre and the bishop on b7.} 13. d5 exd5 14.
exd5 b5 15. b3 $16 {White has a favourable version of Benoni pawn structure.
Malaniuk,V (2522)-Ovsejevitsch,S (2568) Koszalin 2007}) ({The second approach
is} 6... d5 7. Bg5 Bg7 8. cxd5 exd5 {Here I found a rather surprising new idea:
} 9. h4 $5 $146 {This pawn attack is not that uncommon any more and it is used
against many g6-based defences nowadays. I have analyzed the following three
logical responses:} h6 (9... O-O 10. h5 c5 11. e3 Nbd7 12. O-O-O {Naturally,
White castles on the opposite side from where he wants to attack. His chances
seem promising.}) (9... h5 10. e3 O-O (10... Nbd7 {is dubious in the view of}
11. Nb5 {and White wins material.}) 11. g4 $1 hxg4 12. h5 {and White breaks
through on the kingside. His attack is very dangerous, for instance:} gxf3 13.
h6 Bh8 14. h7+ Kg7 15. Bh6+ Kxh7 16. Bxf8+ Kg8 17. Bh6 $16 {with material
advantage.}) 10. Bxf6 $1 {This speeds up White's initiative.} (10. Bf4 a6 {
is pretty unclear.}) 10... Bxf6 11. O-O-O O-O (11... Nd7 {allows White to
seize an immediate initiative with:} 12. e4) 12. Ne5 Nd7 13. f4 Bg7 14. e3 c5
15. Kb1 $36 {and White has better chances, as his initiative on the kingisde
looks very realistic.}) ({In not so distant past, the most popular approach
was to double white pawns with} 6... Bxf3 7. exf3 {I prefer this recapture to
7.gxf3 because it opens up the light-squared bishop and adds to white pawn
mass on the kingside, which may be useful in the attack. A possible downside
is that it disconnects white central pawns, so white needs to pay attention to
his d4-pawn.} Bg7 (7... Nc6 8. Be3 Bg7 {is covered through a different move
order.}) 8. Be3 O-O ({Black has tried} 8... d5 {a few times.} 9. cxd5 exd5 {
This was played in Sokolov, I (2655)-Nikolic, P (2650) Dordrecht 2002 and now,
similar to 6...d5 line above, I propose an attractive new approach:} 10. h4 $1
$146 O-O 11. O-O-O c6 12. g4 {with initiative.}) (8... Nc6 {provokes White to
push} 9. d5 Ne7 10. O-O-O {and here we have two games:} Nf5 ({Another game
featured} 10... O-O 11. dxe6 fxe6 {Perelshteyn,E (2493)-Benjamin,J (2526)
Saint Louis 2018. Here, once again, I like the direct attacking approach
against the fianchetto:} 12. h4 $146 Nf5 13. g4 Nxe3 14. fxe3 $36 {White
initiative on the kingisde looks very promising.}) 11. dxe6 fxe6 12. Bg5 c5 {
An important improvement over the game Saravana, K (2345)-Karthikeyan, P (2502)
Mumbai 2017 is:} 13. Ne2 $1 $146 O-O 14. h4 $36 {with a complicated position
that looks more promising for White due to good central control and attacking
prospects on the kingside.}) 9. h4 $1 {This is the key motif in this variation.
White should not hesitate to launch the pawn storm on black king while Black
has still not created serious counterplay in the centre. After:} Nc6 10. O-O-O
d5 11. cxd5 exd5 12. g4 Na5 13. h5 {White initiative develops on its own.} Re8
14. hxg6 hxg6 15. Bd3 c6 {All of this was quite logical in the game Gershon, A 
(2502)-Anastasian, A (2571) Saint Vincent 2000 and now:} 16. g5 $146 Nh7 17. f4
{would give White serious attacking prospects.}) 7. e4 Nc6 {This is the most
challenging continuation.} (7... cxd4 {has been played more often, but it
looks like an advantageous Hedgehog middlegame for White after} 8. Nxd4 d6 ({or
} 8... Bg7 {when I like the following aggressive development scheme:} 9. Bg5 $1
h6 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 O-O {Hargittay,S-Sarkadi,L Stockerau 1993} 12. O-O-O $1
$146 Nc6 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. f3 Nh5 15. Bd6 $16 {and this is clearly better for
White.}) 9. Be2 Bg7 (9... a6 {is quite similar to the main line:} 10. O-O Nbd7
11. Rd1 Bg7 12. Nf3 $1 {It may seem counter-intuitive to remove the knight
from a commanding central position, but considering that Black has developed
his bishop on g7, this move allows White to hit the vulnerable d6-pawn. This
position and Nd4-f3 manoeuvre is quite similar to one variation of the Kan
Sicilian.} Qc7 (12... O-O {runs into} 13. Bf4 $1) 13. Bf4 {and now Black has
no choice but to compromise his pawn structure with} Ne5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Be3
$16 {allowing an obviously favourable pawn transformation for White as his
queenside majority is a great asset in many endgames. Bruzon Batista, L (2661)
-Zavarce,O (2391) Paramaribo 2017}) (9... Nbd7 10. O-O a6 11. Rd1 {is covered
through 9...a6.}) 10. O-O $146 {Surprisingly, this is a new move. White has
played only 10. Be3 before, but the bishop can be utilized more effectively on
f4 to target the pawn on d6.} a6 11. Nf3 Nbd7 (11... O-O {runs into annoying}
12. Bf4 $14) 12. Bf4 {Black can already feel the pressure against d6-pawn.} Nc5
(12... d5 {is not the solution. It is definitely premature to open the centre
with such a lag in development, and after:} 13. exd5 exd5 14. Bd6 $1 Nc5 15.
Bxc5 bxc5 16. cxd5 {Black has to accept a loss of a pawn because he cannot
recapture on d5 in the view of 17. Rad1.}) {and now White obtains a favorable
middlegame with:} 13. e5 dxe5 14. Nxe5 {when his excellent central control and
pawn majority on the queenside give him a very promising position.} O-O 15.
Rad1 Qe7 16. b4 Nce4 17. Na4 $16 {White is clearly better.}) 8. d5 Nd4 9. Qd1
$146 {I believe that this is an important novelty. White ignores the
opportunity to win a pawn and prefers to keep a slight positional pressure
instead.} (9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Nb5 a6 11. Nxd4 {wins a pawn, but after} Bg7 12.
Bg5 Qc7 {Black has interesting compensation.}) 9... exd5 {This exchange is
called for} ({since} 9... Bg7 {allows} 10. e5 $1 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 Ng8 12. Bf4 Ne7
13. h4 $40 {with initiative.}) 10. cxd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O {Once again,
we have a Benoni type of structure. It is a bit unusual as we rarely see a
knight on d4 in such positions at such an early stage. However, white can
still claim an edge here due to the misplaced position of black light-squared
bishop. It is very difficult to see how this piece could participate in the
game. One possible continuation is} Re8 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 $14 *

