{[%evp 0,49,80,44,20,-12,-11,-16,30,19,17,9,8,4,9,-5,15,2,76,47,-7,7,23,1,-42,
-52,-42,-20,-7,-11,0,-11,-12,-12,-9,-1,26,25,19,21,23,3,13,14,37,5,16,17,14,10,
14,-17]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 d5 {This is the main
continuation after 4...Bb7. Black fights for the centre in a direct manner.} 6.
cxd5 {I prefer this approach over 6.Bg5, which is another major variation. It
makes sense to make this exchange early because it is not so beneficial for
Black to take back with a pawn - it leads to a good version of Queen's gambit
declined for White, as we will see in Chapter 10.} Nxd5 7. Qc2 {This is not
the only good possibility for White, but it is the most straightforward - he
prepares to build a strong pawn centre with 8.e4.} Nxc3 {This is the most
common move.} ({A slightly less flexible setup for Black is} 7... Nd7 8. e4
Nxc3 9. bxc3 Be7 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O c5 {In this line, this thematic pawn move
comes a bit late, so White can take advantage of it by going:} 12. Bf4 {
which prevents the development of the black queen to c7.} Rc8 13. Qe2 {An
important position for this line. Black usually opens the c-file:} cxd4 ({
An obvious alternative is} 13... Nf6 {keeping the tension in the centre. Here,
my choice would be positional:} 14. Bd2 {which prevents the idea of
penetration to c3 by black rook, potentially followed by a positional exchange
sacrifice on d3 and capture of important e4-pawn.} Qc7 15. a4 {The position
assumed a manoeuvring character and this is a very typical way to strengthen
the white position. White plans to push the a-pawn forward, creating some
weaknesses for Black in the process.} Rfd8 16. Rfb1 Qc6 17. Re1 h6 18. a5 b5 {
And here, I suggest a new idea:} 19. a6 $5 $146 Ba8 ({The point is that} 19...
Bxa6 $6 {runs into} 20. e5 Ne8 ({Black has to keep an eye on e4-square since} 
