22. dxe5 $16 {and White was obviously better in Hoffmann, M (2455)-Papp, G (2471)
Budapest 2004}) 19. Ne4 Qd5 20. Rad1 Rc6 21. h4 $1 b5 22. h5 h6 23. Rg3 $40 {
White's attack is quite dangerous. Szabo,V (2445)-Kuhne,D (2354) LSS email 2008})
18. Rad1 Qd5 ({Black was not successful with:} 18... Rc8 19. h4 h6 20. Bf4 Be7
21. Ne1 Qd5 ({obviously, h4-pawn is untouchable:} 21... Bxh4 22. Qh5 $18 Be7
23. Rg3 {with a crushing attack.}) 22. Rg3 Bxh4 23. Rh3 Bg5 24. Bxg5 hxg5 25.
Qh5 f6 26. Nf3 $40 {witha dangerous attack. Kupsys, A (2542)-Dzenis, R (2466)
ICCF email 2009}) 19. h4 {Not only an important attacking but also a defensive
move, as it is always good to give some air to the king in such double-edged
positions as a prophylactic measure against bank-rank checkmate.} f6 {This is
the safest continuation, but it creates some positional weaknesses.} ({On the
other hand, after} 19... h6 20. Bf4 Rc8 (20... f5 {from the game Litz,
K-Kleiner, A GER email 2008, should be met with} 21. Nh2 $1 $146 Rf7 22. Qh5 {
with nice attacking prospects for White after Rg3.}) 21. Nh2 {This is a very
important preparatory move for white attack and another reason why h4 is such
an important conceptual move. This backward knight move opens the third rank for
the rook, while also clearing diagonal for the queen. Moreover, the knight can
join the attack via g4-square.} Kh7 22. Rg3 Rh8 23. Ng4 $40 {Black was in
trouble in Taner,H (2248)-Cehajic,M (2229) IECC email 2012}) 20. exf6 Bxf6 21.
Re3 h6 22. Bf4 Rae8 23. Bg3 Rf7 24. a4 {White's positional advantage is pretty
obvious. Parmet,D (1689)-Langer,R (2273) LSS email 2011}) ({Third option is} 
15... Qc6 16. Bg5 Rfe8 ({Black should definitely avoid} 16... Bxg5 $6 {which,
as we have already seen, only helps White achieve a nice piece regrouping:} 17.
Nxg5 cxd4 18. cxd4 Rac8 19. Rad1 h6 20. Ne4 Qd5 21. Rg3 f5 22. Nd6 Rc6 23. f4
$16 {White was much better in Agrest,E (2592)-Akesson,R (2466) Gothenburg 2005}
) ({However,} 16... Rae8 {looks like a solid alternative.} 17. Rad1 h6 (17...
f6 {is not bad, but doesn't solve Black's problems fully.} 18. exf6 Bxf6 19.
Re3 cxd4 20. cxd4 Qd5 21. Bxf6 Rxf6 22. Rc1 $14 {Black controls the open
c-file and puts pressure on backward e-pawn, so he can claim a small, but
stable advantage. Pankratov,V-Kupsys,A RCCA corr 2004}) 18. Bf4 Rc8 19. d5 {
White breaks through in the center.} (19. Ne1 $5 {preparing rook transfer to
g3, was worth considering.}) 19... exd5 20. Rxd5 Nb8 21. e6 fxe6 22. Re5 Rf6
23. Re4 $44 {with powerful compensation, due to weak black pawn structure on
the kingside Cannon,A (2208)-Muzyka,Y (2369) ICCF email 2013}) 17. Rad1 h6 (
17... c4 18. Re3 Bxa3 {White gets an easy attack on the kingside:} 19. Nd2 b5 {
1-0 (29) Jankovic,A (2444)-Kragelj,I (2247) Pardubice 2004} 20. Qh5 $40) 18.
Bxe7 Rxe7 19. Nd2 cxd4 20. cxd4 f6 21. Nf3 $14 {and White keeps a slight
positional pressure in Kahl, F (2469)-Rodriguez Landa, M (2457) ICCF email 2013
½-½ (31)}) 16. h4 {This is an important part of White's attacking puzzle, as
we have seen on many occasions.} cxd4 (16... Nf8 {was a solid, but quite a
passive try in Krasenkow, M (2635)-Negi, P (2480) Vlissingen 2006. I would
improve White's play with} 17. Ng5 $1 $146 cxd4 18. cxd4 Rd8 19. Qh5 Bxg5 20.
Bxg5 Rd5 21. Rc1 Qe8 22. Qg4 {White maintains better chances due to the passivity
of Black's knight and strong potential of kingside attack, especially on the
g7-pawn.}) 17. cxd4 {Black needs to look for counterplay on the c-file. I
examined three different queen's moves here.} Qb7 (17... Qc4 18. Bg5 h6 (18...
Bf8 {avoids the exchange of bishops but does not slow down white attack:} 19.
Nd2 Qd5 {Gershon,A (2524)-Angelopoulos,G (2104) Athens 2004} 20. Re1 $146 Rac8
21. Qg4 $40 {with great attacking chances.}) 19. Rc1 Qa6 20. Bxe7 Rxe7 {
and here in the game Zakhartsov, V (2578)-Battey, A (2353) Budapest 2012 White
should have continued} 21. Nd2 $1 $146 {heading to d6, with an obvious
advantage. The black knight is much more passive than its white counterpart.}) ({
Secondly, in case of} 17... Qa6 {White can continue:} 18. Ng5 $5 Rac8 19. Qe4
Nf8 20. Qf3 {suddenly targeting f7-pawn. We have not seen this attacking idea
before, but it becomes possible when the rook is not on f8. Now Black has to
part with his bishop:} Bxg5 21. Bxg5 h6 22. Bxh6 $1 {A rather surprising
sacrifice. White was fully in control after} gxh6 23. Qg4+ Ng6 24. Rg3 Kh7 25.
h5 Rg8 26. hxg6+ Rxg6 27. Qf3 Rxg3 28. fxg3 $16 {because black king is more
exposed in Arounopoulos,S (2328)-Huzita,S (2181) ICCF email 2015}) 18. Bg5 Bf8
19. Nd2 f6 {It's hard to give good advice to Black in this passive position.
It seems like White is the one having must of the fun and that he might just
have to weaken his structure with this move sooner or later.} 20. exf6 Nxf6 21.
Bxf6 gxf6 22. Ne4 {White attack was very powerful in Gupta, A (2610)-Ivanchuk, V
(2725) Caleta 2018} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
