[White "Chapter 6 "]
[Black "4...Bb7 5.Nc3 d5 - Part 3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E12"]
[Annotator "GM Boris Avrukh"]
[PlyCount "39"]
[EventDate "2017.09.03"]
[EventType "k.o."]
[EventRounds "7"]
[SourceVersionDate "2019.01.01"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Qc2 Be7 8. e4
Nxc3 9. bxc3 O-O ({As a side note, early} 9... c5 {is slightly inaccurate, as
it allows} 10. Bb5+ $1 {provoking Black bishop to c6, where it is not placed
so well as on b7.} Bc6 11. Bd3 {The bishop returns after completing its
temporary purpose on b5.} O-O 12. O-O Nd7 13. Bf4 cxd4 ({In case of} 13... Bb7
{White has an opportunity for thematic} 14. d5 $1 exd5 15. exd5 Nf6 (15... Bxd5
{looks dangerous for Black in the view of} 16. Bxh7+ Kh8 17. Bf5 $40) 16. c4 {
with a clear positional advantage in Jovanic, O (2490)-Shevchenko, K (2537)
Trieste 2017. White's central bind is a long-term positional asset.}) 14. cxd4
Rc8 15. Qe2 Nf6 {This was seen in Guevara,J (2413)-Toedter,H (2323) ICCF email
2009 and now I like} 16. a4 $146 Bb4 17. h3 $14 {with a definitely more
pleasant position for White.}) 10. Bd3 c5 11. O-O Qc7 {This move has been
considered to be the critical test of Petrosian variation in modern times.} 12.
Qe2 Nd7 ({An obvious alternative is} 12... Nc6 {Both knight moves have their
pros and cons. I believe that in this case, White should go for direct} 13. d5 (
{since} 13. Be3 Rfd8 {looks very like a very comfortable position for Black,})
({as well as} 13. Bb2 Rfd8) 13... Na5 ({Black can also include a pawn exchange:
} 13... exd5 14. exd5 Na5 {Here I discovered a new idea} 15. Qe4 $5 $146 {
White initiates sharp play by provoking kingside weaknesses.} (15. c4 b5 {
looks just fine for Black as he undermines white pawn centre right in time.})
15... g6 ({In case of} 15... f5 16. Qe6+ Kh8 17. c4 Nb3 18. Rb1 Nxc1 19. Rfxc1
{White is slightly better because f7-f5 is a more serious positional
concession compared to g7-g6.}) 16. Bh6 Rfd8 ({The other rook move} 16... Rfe8
{may be riskier due to the pin:} 17. Rfe1 Rad8 18. Bb5 $1 Bxd5 19. Qe5 Qxe5
20. Nxe5 $14 {and I am not sure whether Black gets full compensation for the
exchange.}) 17. c4 b5 {This typical undermining move works well here, too.
However, White is much better developed, so he keeps a slight edge after:} 18.
Rad1 Nxc4 19. Bxc4 bxc4 20. Qxc4 $14 {Black position looks somewhat vulnerable
due to the weak dark squares.}) 14. c4 Nb3 ({After} 14... exd5 {surprisingly
no one recaptured with c-pawn. Still, after} 15. cxd5 $146 c4 16. Bc2 Nb3 17.
Bxb3 cxb3 18. Rd1 {in spite of very complicated double-edged play, I like
White chances.}) 15. Rb1 Nxc1 16. Rfxc1 {We reached an interesting position.
White has a clear space advantage, but Black is hoping to compensate for it
with its bishop pair. However, due to the closed nature of the position, it is
difficult for the bishops to show serious activity, especially the one on b7.
Examples below show that White can increase his positional pressure.} Rfe8 ({
Another good model game here is} 16... Rad8 17. a4 $1 {A very typical plan.
White often uses his rook's pawns in Petrosian variation, sometimes for
kingside, other time for queenside attack.} Rfe8 18. a5 bxa5 19. Qa2 f5 $2 {
This runs into an elegant refutation:} 20. e5 exd5 21. Rxb7 $1 Qxb7 22. cxd5 {
and White achieved a winning position in Nesterov, A (2378)-Lobanov, S (2539) St
Petersburg 2018 as Black is helplessly weak on the light squares after the
exchange sacrifice.}) 17. Bc2 {preparing to transfter the bishop to a4.} exd5
18. cxd5 Bf6 19. Qc4 Rad8 20. Re1 g6 21. Rbd1 Qd6 22. Re3 Bg7 23. a4 {White is
fully in control, thanks to his pawn majority in the centre Pierzak, R (2494)
-Teeriaho, T (2405) ICCF email 2012.}) 13. a4 $1 {In this line, I prefer
positional over the attacking approach. The plan with a4-a5 is quite thematic
and we have examined it already in some lines in this and previous chapters.} (
{Unlike the 13...Qc8 variation, the attacking plan} 13. e5 {does not seem so
convincing to me after} Rfd8 {because black light-squared bishop often
interferes with White's attacking plans.}) 13... Rfd8 {This is the most
logical continuation as the rook is useful on d-file, while it also clears
f8-square for the knight manoeuvre to g6.} ({I also examined two other
alternatives:} 13... Rac8 14. Bd2 {Here, Black can block the centre in a
typical way:} e5 15. Rfc1 c4 16. Bc2 Ba6 {This occurred in Kolanek, R (1913)
-Hatsek, W (1925) LSS email 2013. Now I believe that White should start
regrouping with} 17. Rd1 $146 Rfe8 18. Rab1 {followed by Be3 would lead to
White better position. White has more flexibility in the centre, while it is
not so easy to suggest a useful move for Black.}) ({and:} 13... Rfe8 14. Rd1 h6
15. g3 a6 16. Rb1 Bc6 17. Bc2 cxd4 18. cxd4 Qb7 19. Nd2 Nf6 20. Qd3 $1 $40 {
White was able to generate dangerous initiative in Baer, L (2332)-Piccoli, F 
(2277) ICCF email 2016}) 14. Bd2 Rac8 ({The main alternative is} 14... Nf8 {
and here is the game which inspired me to cover the whole Petrosian variation:}
15. a5 Ng6 16. g3 $1 {Black knight should be restricted.} Bc6 17. h4 {White
plays on the whole board. This is indeed a model game.} h6 (17... h5 {looks
too weakening. After:} 18. Rfc1 Qb7 19. Bg5 f6 20. Bd2 b5 21. a6 Qd7 22. Bc2 {
White's advantage is beyond any doubts as black kingside has been seriously
weakened Civitillo, A (2460)-Caglia, G (1929) ICCF email 2009.}) 18. Rfe1 Bf6 19.
h5 Nf8 20. Bf4 Qe7 {So far White has played perfectly in the game Wojtaszek, R 
(2745)-El Debs,F (2531) Tbilisi 2017. If he had continued:} 21. e5 $1 $146 Bg5
22. Bxg5 (22. Nxg5 hxg5 23. Be3 {is also better for White.}) 22... hxg5 23. Be4
{he could have claimed a clear advantage immediately.}) 15. g3 {This move
apparently weakens white king, but it is, in fact, an important part of the
system as it not only covers f4-square from intrusion but also prepares
unpleasant Bf4.} a5 ({After:} 15... e5 16. Rfc1 c4 17. Bc2 Ba6 18. Rd1 $14 {
we have a similar position to the one discussed in one of the previous variations.
Provoking c5-c4 favours White, in my opinion, as it reduces pressure against
white centre.}) 16. Bf4 Bd6 17. Bg5 Re8 18. Nd2 h6 19. Be3 Red8 20. Rfd1 {
White has a slightly better game, as in Oreopoulos, K (2450)-Kubicki, T (2429)
ICCF email 2013. He has a wider range of manoeuvring options. Black's position
is solid but somewhat reactive, rather than proactive. White may put pressure
on both sides of the board (on b6 pawn or with moves like h4-h5 on the
kingside), while Black needs to wait for the appropriate moment to
counter-attack.} *

