{[%evp 0,31,14,30,29,0,6,6,27,16,24,9,18,14,22,53,98,110,81,65,102,73,77,-47,
-8,14,4,6,37,3,31,76,111,95]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Ba6 {By
playing like this, Black approaches the Petrosian system in a much different
way than we have seen so far. This is very similar to variation 4.g3 Ba6,
where he immediately attacks c4-pawn and tries to provoke a certain concession
from White. For example, 5.e3 and 5.Nbd2 block the dark-squared bishop. The
main move is} 5. Qc2 {when Black usually retreats the bishop to b7 and
continues 6...c5, using the fact that the queen is not on d1 any more to
support 7.d5. This will be the subject of upcoming chapters but in this one,
I would like to check the immediate} c5 {However, in this case, White can push
the central pawn} 6. d5 {freely, since after} exd5 7. cxd5 {it can not be
captured due to 8.Qe4+, winning material. Thus, we have a Benoni pawn
structure, just like in Chapter 1. In this case, the inclusion of moves Ba6 and
Qc2 seems to be more useful for Black, considering how passive his
light-squared bishop was in similar positions in Chapter 1. He would be happy
to trade it off after e4, Bxf1, which would also disrupt White's castling.} g6
({Another move order is} 7... d6 8. Nc3 g6 {when White can apply the same idea
as in the main line:} 9. h4 $1 h5 ({In case of} 9... Bg7 {White sacrifices a
pawn:} 10. h5 Nxh5 11. g4 $1 $146 {I think that this is stronger and more
convincing} ({than} 11. Rxh5 gxh5 12. Ne4 O-O $2 ({However, Black should have
played} 12... f5 $1 13. Neg5 Bc8 14. Bf4 Qf6 15. O-O-O O-O {with double-edged
play.}) 13. Nfg5 f5 14. Ne6 Qh4 15. Nxd6 $18 {and White achieved a decisive
edge in Mitsis,G (2326)-Balokas,D (2250) Anogia 2018}) 11... Nf6 12. Bh6 {
The attacking motif where White sacrifices the pawn to open h-file and then
trades fianchettoed dark-squared bishop is well-known from many openings. It
works very well here, too. It should also be noted that Black can not take the
g4-pawn due to Qe4+.} Bxh6 (12... O-O {is a very dangerous idea for Black.
After:} 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. g5 Nh5 ({or} 14... Ne8 15. O-O-O) 15. Rxh5 $1 gxh5
16. Ne4 {white initiative looks very promising.}) 13. Rxh6 Bc8 14. g5 Ng4 15.
Rh4 {with fantastic compensation for White. Black development is very poor and
his extra pawn is meaningless in such a position.}) (9... h6 {was tried in
Bosboom,M (2419)-Iordachescu,V (2606) Dieren 2005. An obvious improvement here
is} 10. h5 $1 g5 ({In case of} 10... Nxh5 11. g4 Nf6 {White easily develops a powerful initiative with} 12. g5 Nh5 13. Ne4 Bg7 14. Rxh5 gxh5 15. gxh6 Rxh6
16. Bg5 $40) {and White can use weakening of f5-square in the following way:}
11. e4 Bxf1 12. Kxf1 Bg7 13. Ne2 $1 {White knight is heading to g3,
highlighting black weakness on f5. White chances are definitely better.}) {
In this case, there will be no attack with the h-pawn, but White gets a
comfortable outpost for his bishop on g5:} 10. Bg5 Bg7 11. Nd2 {The knight is
headed to e4-square in order to put pressure on f6 and d6.} Bb7 $2 ({It would
have been better to unpin with} 11... Qd7 {Still, White's position is very
attractive after} 12. Nde4 ({or} 12. g3 $5 O-O 13. Bh3) 12... Nxe4 13. Qxe4+
Kf8 14. Rh3) 12. Nde4 Qe7 {This happened in Gupta, A (2619)-Fendereski, N (2268)
Abu Dhabi 2015 and now after a strong and typical rook lift:} 13. Rh3 $146 {
Black cannot avoid losing material, as in the following variation:} O-O 14. Re3
Qd8 15. Rf3 Nbd7 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Rxf6 $1 Nxf6 18. Ne4 {and White wins.}) ({
Technically, Black can win the central pawn after:} 7... Bb7 8. e4 Qe7 {
but that delays his kingside development significantly and White obtains
serious initiative with:} 9. Bd3 Nxd5 ({The other capture is worse:} 9... Bxd5
10. Nc3 Bc6 11. O-O d6 {Benjamin, J (2565)-Kramer, C Chicago 1987 and after} 12.
Bg5 $146 {black position is already very difficult due to development issues.})
10. Bg5 {I prefer this inclusion for White, compared to 10.0-0.} f6 (10... Nf6
{is pretty bad. White achieved a crushing victory in the following game:} 11.
Nc3 h6 12. Bf4 Nh5 13. Bc7 Bc6 14. O-O-O d6 15. Nb5 Qd7 16. e5 $18 {Artemiev,V
(2655)-Petrosyan,M (2549) Moscow 2017}) 11. O-O Nc7 12. Bf4 {Even though the
position is still somewhat closed, White's lead in development is huge and
Black is facing definite difficulties.} Ne6 ({The alternative is:} 12... d6 13.
Nc3 Nd7 14. b4 {This is an excellent idea, reminding Black that his king would
not be safe on the queenside, either.} g5 15. Bg3 Ne5 $6 16. bxc5 bxc5 17. Bxe5
fxe5 18. Qa4+ Qd7 19. Qb3 Bc6 20. Nxg5 {White regained a pawn and remained
with a clear edge in the game Sakaev, K (2570)-Ruban, V (2535) Elista 1995}) 13.
Be3 Nc6 14. Nc3 Qf7 15. Bc4 {control over the a2-g8 diagonal and d5-square
give White an overwhelming positional compensation.} Be7 16. Rad1 Na5 17. Ba2 {
Black struggled in Parsons,L (2310)-Chipkin,L (2171) ICCF email 2012}) 8. Nc3
Bg7 ({For} 8... d6 9. h4 {see 7...d6}) 9. h4 $5 {A very surprsing idea, which
seems to be working great for White in this variation. A more popular approach
used to be 9.g3, which would lead to some kind of Fianchetto Benoni, but
recently this aggressive move has proven to be a headache for Black.} h5 {
We have seen in a similar position in variation 7...d6 what happens if Black
does not block the path of h-pawn. Thus, 9...h5 is the safest option, but it
also creates long-lasting weaknesses.} 10. Bg5 {As a consequence of Black's
previous move, White has obtained a nice outpost on g5.} O-O {This is too
dangerous. Black should have probably completed his queenside development with
10...d6, transposing into variation 7...d6.} 11. g4 $1 {Black may have
underestimated this powerful attacking idea.} hxg4 12. h5 Qe8 ({The point is
that Black can not take the piece} 12... gxf3 {because White wins even more
material with} 13. h6 Bh8 14. h7+) {This happened in Gupta-Fier, Reykjavik
2015 and now White missed the decisive:} 13. hxg6 $146 gxf3 (13... fxg6 14. Nh4
Nh7 15. Bd2 {is also terrible for Black.}) 14. Bxf6 fxg6 (14... Bxf6 {loses to}
15. g7 $18) 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. O-O-O $40 {and White attack is decisive since
Black is not in time to transfer his queenside piece to king's defence.} *

