{[%evp 0,33,14,29,29,4,4,6,28,15,22,18,34,32,29,-21,-19,-1,8,16,-6,-96,-14,8,
-6,-26,22,16,34,22,-4,-4,3,-2,15,8]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Ba6 5.
Qc2 Bb7 {This is the main continuation in 4...Ba6 variation. After} 6. Nc3 c5 {
7.d5 does not work that well for White due to 7...exd5 8.cxd5 Nxd5 and if 9.
Qe4+ now there is 9...Qe7.  Nevertheless, White can establish pawn advantage
in the centre with} 7. e4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 {which leads to a type of pawn
structure that we have not met so far. This kind of position sometimes arises
from the symmetrical English opening when White plays early d4. This usually
leads to Hedgehog type of position after Black entrenches with d6, Be7, etc. 
However, in this case, he can set up a different strategy:} Bc5 {This has been
Black's most popular move in this position and will be the topic of this
chapter. We will discuss alternatives 8...Nc6 and 8...d6 in the next two
chapters. The aim of 8...Bc5 is to fight for d4-square with Nc6 and sometimes
even d6 and e5.} 9. Nf3 $5 {I believe that this knight retreat is more
interesting compared with a much more popular 9.Nb3, which is considered to be
pretty solid for Black. Black's point is that he can simply continue
developing with 9...Nc6 and if 10.Nxc5 bxc5, he can eventually strengthen his
control over d4-square with d6 and e5, fully compensating for the lack of
bishop pair.} Ng4 {This is definitely the most principled response. However,
White can elegantly solve problems with vulnerable f-pawn} ({The alternatives
are:} 9... Nc6 10. b4 Nd4 $5 {Black can continue fighting for central squares
with this move,} ({although it goes without saying Black can retreat and keep
it solid with:} 10... Be7 11. Bf4 Nh5 12. Be3 Qb8 13. Qd2 {White needs to make
sure that f4-square has been covered so that he can complete his development
with Be2,0-0 etc. At the same time, the queen is very useful on d2 as it controls
d-file.} O-O 14. Be2 Rd8 15. O-O Nf6 16. Rfd1 d6 17. Rac1 Rd7 18. h3 $14 {
and White obtained an active and promising position in Ragger, M (2639)
-Zhigalko, A (2585) Warsaw 2014. It seems like the black knight is somewhat
misplaced on c6 since it usually belongs on d7 in the Hedgehog.}) (10... Bd6 {
is a more active retreat - Black is looking to obtain control over h2-b8
diagonal. After} 11. Bb2 Qb8 (11... O-O {was seen in Swiercz, D (2609)-Idani, P 
(2470) Maribor 2012} {when} 12. Rd1 $146 {looks quite natural and after:} Bb8
13. Na4 $1 $14 {Black can not play 13...Ne5, which makes his position cramped.}
Qe7 14. Be2 d6 15. O-O {and I believe that this Hedgehog version is favourable
for White, due to the passive position of black dark-squared bishop.}) 12. Nb5
Bf4 {This occurred in Esen, B (2563)-Kovalenko, I (2650) Iasi 2015, and here I
can offer the following improvement:} 13. Rd1 $146 a6 14. e5 $1 {A strong idea.
Now we see why it was important to start with 13.Rd1 -Black can not take
e5-pawn due to Nd6+ and he loses a piece on e5. Therefore,} axb5 {is forced,
when White gets an advantage after:} 15. exf6 g6 16. Qc3 d6 17. cxb5 Ne5 18.
Be2 Qc8 19. Qb3) 11. Qd2 {This queen move is more active than Qd1 and more
precise than Qd3 because queen will be the most useful on d2 in the arising
position.} Nxf3+ ({White should not fear} 11... Nb3 {since} 12. Qb2 {forces a
favourable trade of two pieces for a rook and a pawn.}) 12. gxf3 {It may seem
like this is a positional weakening, but it actually helps White mobilize his
king's rook for attack along the g-file. Clearly, in that case, White will
castle queenside.} Be7 13. Bb2 a5 {This looks critical to me.} ({Certainly
Black has tried other moves as well:} 13... a6 {For some reason, white players
have never tried logical} 14. O-O-O $146 {in practice. After:} O-O 15. Rg1 g6
16. Kb1 {White has very good prospects for a kingside attack with his bishop on
g2 and open g-file. Moves like Qh6, h4-h5 or well prepared f4-f5 break also
look attractive for White. Meanwhile, it is not that easy for Black to
organize strong counterplay on the other side of the board.}) ({Very similar
is:} 13... O-O 14. Rg1 d6 15. O-O-O {White position is very attractive. The
following game is a nice example of White's attacking resources:} Rc8 $6 16.
Nb5 $1 Ba6 17. Nxd6 $1 Bxd6 18. Rxg7+ Kh8 19. Qh6 e5 20. Rxd6 Qxd6 21. Rxh7+ (
21. Rg5 $1 {was easier}) 21... Nxh7 22. Qxd6 $18 {with a decisive advantage
Greenfeld,A (2545)-Postny,E (2631) Bastia 2013}) 14. Nb5 {White sacrifices a
pawn to win the bishop pair.} (14. b5 $5 {keeping queenside closed, is also
worthy of consideration.}) 14... axb4 15. Nd6+ Bxd6 16. Qxd6 b3 ({I was unable
to figure out what was the idea behind} 16... Qe7 $2 {in the game Freitag,M 
(2387)-Farago,I (2377) Austria 2017} 17. Qxb6 $146 {seems to be just winning
material on the spot.}) 17. Rg1 Nh5 18. O-O-O Bc6 {and now in the game Ragger,
M (2657)-Ruck, R (2572) Bilbao 2014, White would have maintained better chances
with} 19. Bd4 $14 {with impressive control of dark squares on the whole board.}
) ({and} 9... O-O {which, however, is not that good, as it allows White to
expand his space advantage with:} 10. b4 Be7 11. e5 $1 Ne8 (11... Ng4 12. h3
Nh6 {was not great for Black in Kaabi, M (2327)-Belouadah, S (2342) Tipaza 2011.
A simple:} 13. Bxh6 $146 gxh6 14. Be2 $16 {would secure White a solid
advantage.}) 12. Bd3 f5 13. exf6 Nxf6 {and here White found a good exchanging
sequence to neutralize queen's indian bishop:} 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16.
Qxe4 Nc6 17. O-O Qc7 18. Rd1 Rac8 19. Be3 Bf6 {All this happened in Girya, O 
(2444)-Ju, W (2578) Chengdu 2016. So far White's play was very impressive. She
obtained a clear edge in the view of the superior pawn structure. Now the natural}
20. Rac1 $146 {would seal her positional edge, due to the fact that} Bb2 21.
Rc2 Bxa3 {does not work in the view of} 22. Rcd2 $1 Rcd8 23. Bg5 $18 {with a
decisive advantage.}) {with:} 10. Bg5 $1 f6 (10... Bxf2+ {is obviously bad due
to:} 11. Qxf2 Nxf2 12. Bxd8 Nxh1 13. Bg5 {and White is going to win the
trapped black knight, with a clear edge in Sorensen, H (2154)-Forsberg, A (2048)
Ronneby 2018}) 11. Bh4 Nc6 12. Be2 h5 {This is the critical continuation, in
my opinion. The bishop on h4 starts feeling somewhat uncomfortable.} ({Black
also tried:} 12... O-O 13. Rd1 a6 $6 14. O-O {but here White simply has a
positional advantage since the combination of f6 and Ng4 is not constructive for
Black. He even made it worse with} Qc7 {allowing the following typical
Hedgehog tactic:} 15. Bg3 $1 Nge5 16. b4 Be7 17. Nd5 $1 {and White seized
initiative in Buhmann,R (2612)-Braeuer,F (2413) Germany 2016}) ({and} 12... Rc8
13. Rd1 a5 {Black secures his bishop on c5 with this move.} 14. O-O Nge5 {
This was played in Greenfeld, A (2550)-Viljava, T (2187) Hersonissos 2017 and
now:} 15. Nxe5 $146 Nxe5 16. Kh1 O-O 17. f4 {would have lead to a promising
position for White.}) 13. b4 Be7 {this position occurred in Greenfeld, A (2496)
-Kunin, V (2538) Sandavagur 2018. I believe that White should have tried} 14.
Bg3 $146 {when the game could continue:} Nge5 15. Bxe5 fxe5 16. Qd3 d6 17. Rd1
{with better chances for White due to a clearly superior pawn structure.} *

