{[%evp 0,41,19,25,27,-16,-20,3,27,23,44,25,24,31,35,-1,-12,-9,21,36,29,26,57,4,
18,7,45,10,10,4,64,9,48,31,31,41,41,41,45,45,45,45,59,20]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Ba6 5. Qc2 Bb7 6. Nc3 c5 7. e4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {This is the
second most popular move in this position. White should simply trade the
knights:} 9. Nxc6 Bxc6 (9... dxc6 $6 {is dubious. After} 10. Bf4 {and 11. Rd1
next, the position is very unpleasant for Black, for example:} Nh5 11. Rd1 Qf6
12. Be3 e5 13. Qa4 Bd6 {This occurred in Starke,D (2211)-Peter,S (2234) Hessen
2000. Now, very strong would have been:} 14. c5 $1 $146 bxc5 ({or} 14... Bxc5
15. Bxc5 bxc5 16. Nd5 Qd8 17. Nf4 $1) 15. Ba6 $1 {winning material in both
cases.}) 10. Bf4 {It is very important for White to take control of the h2-b8
diagonal before Black does with moves like Bd6 and Qc7/b8. Now there are three
major moves for Black.} Bc5 ({Black can also fight for the important diagonal
with} 10... Nh5 11. Bd2 $5 Qc7 ({The other way is:} 11... Bd6 12. g3 Nf6 13.
Bg2 a6 {which happened in Paesschesoone,S (2040)-Carter,M (1819) ICCF email
2014. Now} 14. b4 $146 O-O 15. O-O Qc7 16. Qd3 {would have led to a pleasant
advantage for White.}) ({I also looked at} 11... Qf6 12. Qd1 g6 ({White's task
is easier after} 12... Qg6 13. g4 $1 Nf6 14. f3 {White establishes a solid
pawn base and is ready to increase his space advantage with h4.} Bc5 15. h4 h5
16. g5 Ng8 17. Ne2 $16 {White was much better in Carter, M (2032)-Schneider, G
ICCF email 2016 considering his space advantage and poor position of black
queen.}) 13. g3 {White completes his development this way also in 11...Qc7
line.} Bg7 14. Bg2 O-O 15. O-O Qd4 {Schmidt, M-Vosahlik, J (2596) ICCF email
2010. Now I like the following improvement:} 16. b3 $146 f5 17. exf5 exf5 18.
Ra2 $1 {with better prospects for White.}) 12. g3 {This is the most convenient
way to complete development, while also limiting black knight.} Bc5 (12... f5 {
is a sharper alternative. White can continue developing normally, nevertheless:
} 13. Bg2 Bc5 14. O-O O-O {Baranowski, T (2334)-Olano Aizpurua, J (2204) ICCF
email 2015. The most natural continuation is:} 15. b4 $146 Bd4 16. Rac1 {
with a pleasant game.}) 13. Bg2 O-O 14. O-O {This is a fairly typical
middlegame structure in this variation. White has a stable space advantage.}
Rac8 15. Rac1 Nf6 16. b4 Be7 17. Qd3 {White was clearly better in Jobava, B 
(2717)-Timman, J (2601) Hoogeveen 2014}) (10... d6 {is quite passive, but
White can take advantage of it only with aggressive play:} 11. O-O-O Qc7 12.
Be2 Be7 13. g4 $1 O-O 14. g5 Nd7 15. h4 {with a promising Sicilian-like pawn
storm in the game Mraz, M-Fabri, F ICCF corr 1992}) 11. O-O-O {This seems to
me more challenging} ({than more popular} 11. Be2) 11... Nh5 {This is Black's
main move and the main reason why some players prefer apparently safer 11.Be2.}
(11... O-O {was played once. I believe that White can continue} 12. Kb1 $146 {
vacating c1-square for the bishop. A possible line here is:} Nh5 13. Bc1 Qc7
14. h4 $1 Rac8 15. Qe2 Nf4 16. Qf3 e5 17. Nd5 {with a definite initiative for
White.}) (11... a5 {occured in D'Costa, L (2157) -Panchanathan, M (2238)
Witley 2000. Now a clear improvement would be:} 12. Be2 $146 O-O 13. e5 Ne8 14.
Ne4 Be7 15. h4 {with promising attacking chances.}) 12. Bd2 e5 {Black often
takes control over dark squares in the centre this way. The drawback is that
it allows White to assume control of d5-square.} (12... Bxf2 {which occurred
in Pavlidou, E (2185)-Makka, I (2065) Thessaloniki 2018 is too dangerous for
Black. White should just play} 13. Be2 $146 g6 (13... Nf6 14. e5 {is even
worse for Black.}) 14. Bxh5 gxh5 15. Qd3 $1 {and black position is very
unpleasant because of his kingside weaknesses.}) {Now I found an interesting
novelty} 13. Kb1 $146 {once again, with the idea to clear c1-square for the
bishop. The critical test is} Bxf2 ({In case of} 13... O-O 14. Bc1 a5 15. Nd5 {
White enjoys a pleasant advantage.}) 14. Nd5 {White is not too concerned about
the lost pawn. His main goal is to obtain initiative. Black has two misplaced
pieces (Nh5 and Bf2), while the newly opened f-file can prove to be useful for
attacking purposes.} Bc5 (14... O-O {runs into} 15. g4 $1 Bxd5 16. exd5 Nf6 17.
Bg5 Bd4 18. Bd3 h6 19. h4 $1 $40 {with a powerful compensation and good
attacking chances.}) 15. Be2 Nf6 ({In case of} 15... Nf4 {White has a pleasant
choice between initiative-oriented:} 16. Bxf4 ({and more technical:} 16. Nxf4
exf4 17. Bxf4 O-O 18. Bd3 $14) 16... exf4 17. e5 O-O 18. g3 {with promising
play for White in both cases.}) 16. Bg5 {This pin makes Black's defensive task
more difficult} ({than} 16. Rdf1 Nxd5 17. exd5 Bb7 {when he can gradually
prepare queenside castling.}) 16... Be7 17. Rhf1 {Tension has reached its peak.
Black needs to decide how to resolve it.} Nxd5 ({The other option is} 17...
Bxd5 18. cxd5 {In this instance we see another benefit of playing Kb1 - White
does not need to concern himself with Rc8 any more.} h6 ({In case of} 18... d6
19. Qc6+ $1 {is very strong.} Kf8 (19... Nd7 {is refuted by:} 20. Bg4 $1 Bxg5
21. Bxd7+ Kf8 22. Qxd6+ Qe7 23. Qc6 $18) 20. Rc1 $16 {with a complete
positional domination.}) 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. d6 $1 {This is the whole point of
White's strategy. After:} O-O 21. Rf3 Rc8 22. Qa4 {we get a position similar
to the main line.}) 18. cxd5 Ba4 {Black's best try} ({, since after} 18... Bb7
19. Bxe7 Kxe7 20. Qb3 {nothing seems to be right in his position.}) 19. Qxa4
Bxg5 20. d6 $1 {The key move. With it, White fixes the pawn on d7 (light
square!), opens a2-g8 diagonal and creates a possible outpost on c7 for his
heavy pieces, which can become especially important in the endgame.} O-O 21.
Rf3 {and despite being down a pawn, White maintains clearly better chances. It
is well-known that in middlegames with heavy pieces and opposite-coloured
bishops the side with more active pieces has a considerable advantage, and
this position is a good example.} *

