{[%evp 0,29,27,27,27,3,-12,10,25,13,58,27,21,7,32,39,14,21,31,25,22,37,35,23,
27,20,24,21,40,13,81,79]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 d5 5. Nc3 Bb7 6.
cxd5 {Instead of the usual 6...Nxd5, the alternative recapture is} exd5 {
This is considered less principled than the knight recapture because it shuts
down the light-squared bishop. However, Black usually gets a solid, if
somewhat passive Queen's gambit setup with it. Some players prefer such
schemes to more concrete theoretical lines in 6...Nxd5 variation. White has a
wide choice of different set-ups in response, and I decided to go with} 7. Bg5
Be7 ({A major alternative is} 7... Nbd7 8. Qa4 {This double pin is unpleasant
for Black.} c6 (8... Be7 9. e3 {will be covered through 8...Be7 move order.}) (
8... a6 {allows} 9. Ne5 {when Black is virtually forced to play:} b5 10. Qc2 {
and white queen can return happily because it has forced a concession in black
pawn structure.} Be7 11. Nxd7 Nxd7 ({The alternative is} 11... Qxd7 12. e3 O-O
13. Bd3 h6 14. Bh4 {with a pleasant advantage for White because Black has
problems carrying out thematic ...c7-c5.}) 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. g3 {White adopts
fianchetto approach, which makes a lot of sense in a position in which Black
has a pawn on d5 and bishop on b7.} Nf6 14. Bg2 c5 15. dxc5 Rc8 16. O-O Rxc5
17. Qd3 O-O 18. e3 {and White definitely had a very favourable position
against isolated queen's pawn in Tomaszewski, R (2216)-Klekowski, M (2499)
Krakow 2018.}) 9. Ne5 {This direct move looks very attractive in combination
with Qa4 and Bg5.} b5 {This is a serious positional concession.} ({Unpinning
with} 9... Qc7 {looks a bit better, although after:} 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. Rc1 Qd6
12. e3 $14 {it still leads to a pleasant edge for White.}) 10. Qc2 Be7 11. Nxd7
Nxd7 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. e3 {Black's problematic pawn structure on the queenside
and poor bishop promise White a considerable positional advantage. After:} a6
14. Rd1 O-O 15. Be2 {Black tried to break free with} c5 $6 {but this was
hardly a good idea in the view of:} 16. dxc5 Qxc5 17. O-O Rfd8 18. Qf5 Nf6 19.
Rd4 $16 {With a textbook advantage against the isolated pawn in Gupta, A (2630)
-Rozentalis,E (2552) Warsaw 2016}) 8. Qa4+ {Like in 7...Nbd7 variation, this
idea appeals to me. White is trying to force some concessions from Black
before he has castled.} c6 {This is the most solid.} ({Alternatives are:} 8...
Nbd7 9. e3 O-O ({Black can also prevent White's idea with} 9... a6 {when we
simply continue:} 10. Bd3 O-O 11. Bf5 $1 c5 12. O-O b5 13. Qc2 c4 14. Ne5 {
with a double-edged position in which White's initiative is more concrete.} g6
{was played in Leimgruber, R (2063)-Sergiev, S (2283) ICCF email 2008, and here
I prefer:} 15. Bxd7 $146 Nxd7 16. Bh6 Re8 17. f4 {with a promising position
for White.}) 10. Ba6 $1 {Here we can see another idea of Qa4 move - the trade
of light-squared bishops is clearly favourable for him in the arising pawn
structure as Black is left with light-squared weaknesses one the queenside,
and it also becomes more difficult to defend d5-pawn in case he pushes the
pawn to c5.} Bxa6 11. Qxa6 c6 12. O-O {White should have a slight positional
plus here because of weakness on c6.} Qc8 {It makes the most sense to try to
reclaim control of light squares with this move.} (12... Ne4 {did not work
well for Black in the following game:} 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Rac1 Qd6 (14... Nd6 {
would have been better, even though White maintains a pleasant edge after} 15.
Rc2 {preparing to double-up on the c-pawn.}) 15. Nxe4 $1 dxe4 16. Nd2 Nf6 17.
h3 {White already has a strong positional pressure, but next black move makes
it very easy for him:} c5 $2 18. Rxc5 {1-0 (18) Mitkov,M (2333)-Ilic,M (2123)
Struga 2018}) 13. Qxc8 ({I am pretty sure that White is also slightly better
after} 13. Qd3 $5) 13... Rfxc8 14. Rac1 {White has a slightly better endgame
because he will have a target on the c-file or d-file in case of ...c6-c5. It
is suprising how quickly black position collapsed in the following game:} b5 $6
15. Bxf6 gxf6 $2 16. Nh4 Nb6 17. Nf5 {with a large positional advantage in
Khenkin-Epishin, Bolzano 1999.}) ({and:} 8... Bc6 9. Qc2 {Now black
light-squared bishop is misplaced on c6 and he will have to waste a tempo to
retreat it sooner or later. Meanwhile, it is a clear improvement for White to
have his queen on c2 rather than d1, so in this case, Qa4-c2 manoeuvre has
allowed White to win a tempo in the opening, which is not a small matter.} O-O
10. e3 Bb7 11. Bd3 Nbd7 12. O-O {White basically got a normal position from
Tartakower variation of Queen's gambit declined with a tempo up. Here, we have
two illustrative lines:} h6 ({and:} 12... c5 13. Rad1 c4 14. Bf5 {The bishop
feels very comfortable on this square in such positions, exerting pressure on
both d7 and h7.} g6 15. Bh3 Nh5 16. Bh6 Re8 17. Qa4 $1 {This is quite
unpleasant for Black.} Ndf6 18. Ne5 Bd6 19. f4 $16 {and White seized serious
initiative in Swiercz,D (2609)-Socko,M (2445) St Petersburg 2012.}) 13. Bh4 Re8
14. Rad1 {This is a useful prophylactic move against 14...c5 because the rook
could prove very useful on d-file in that case.} c6 {This move prepares a
thematic simplification manoeuvre...Nf6-e4 by supporting d5-pawn.} ({The
immediate} 14... Ne4 $6 {runs into an elegant refutation:} 15. Nxd5 $1 Bxd5 16.
Bxe4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Bxa3 18. Qc6 Be7 19. Bg3 $16 {with a clear positional
advantage for White in Balcerak,J (2445)-Bosiocic,M (2566) Germany 2016.}) 15.
Rfe1 Ne4 {This position was reached in Stimpel-Rosen, Potsdam 1997. Now White
should have played} 16. Bxe4 $146 Bxh4 17. Bh7+ Kh8 18. Bf5 Nf8 19. e4 $1 $14 {
with a better game since Black will have a hard time involving his
light-squared bishop in the game.}) 9. e3 O-O 10. Bd3 c5 {This is the most
straightforward continuation.} ({Black has other possibilities:} 10... Ne4 11.
Bxe4 Bxg5 12. Nxg5 Qxg5 13. Bf3 {despite simplifications, Black hasn't
achieved equality because his passive light-squared bishop is a long-term
issue. The following game saw:} Na6 14. O-O Nc7 15. Rac1 Rfd8 16. g3 Ne6 17.
Bg2 Qe7 18. Rfd1 $14 {and White is always slightly, but surely better in this
pawn structure, as in Bareev-Huebner, Munich 1993. This usually leads to a
manoeuvring fight in which White can combine queenside play with b2-b4, Qa4-b3
and then a4-a5 or b4-b5, with a permanent threat of favourably opening the
centre with the e3-e4 break. Meanwhile, Black's position is quite passive and he
is mostly in reactive mode.}) ({and} 10... Nbd7 11. O-O Re8 ({I would like to
mention the following game:} 11... c5 12. Rad1 Ne4 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. dxc5 $1 {
This is a very strong tactical motif. After} Nxc5 15. Rxd8 Bxd8 16. Qc2 {
the draw was agreed in Khalifman, A (2530)-Naumkin, I (2440) Riga 1988, but I
believe that White is clearly better after:} exf3 17. Bxd8 fxg2 18. Rd1 Raxd8
19. Rxd8 Rxd8 20. e4 $16) 12. Qc2 {Once again, queen retreats to c2 upon
completing its job on a4. The arising position has many similarities to
Queen's Gambit Declined. Black is very solid, but his options are limited. He
can either try to trade some pieces with ...Nf6-e4 or prepare ...c7-c5. White
should be ready for both.} c5 (12... g6 {takes away f5-square from white
bishop.} 13. Rad1 ({A different rook arrangement:} 13. Rfd1 a6 14. Rac1 $5 $146
{deserves attention, too.}) 13... Rc8 14. Rfe1 {White is just being flexible,
but so is Black:} a6 {This was played in Gurevich, M (2669)-Spraggett, K (2592)
Andorra 2005. It was an approriate moment for the central break:} 15. e4 $146 {
After:} dxe4 16. Bxe4 $1 Nd5 17. h4 {white advantage is pretty obvious.}) 13.
Rad1 c4 ({In case of} 13... Ne4 {Bagirov,R (2481)-Bakre,T (2352) St Petersburg
2000, I believe that White should refrain from trading dark-squared bishops by
playing} 14. Bf4 $146 Ndf6 15. dxc5 $1 Nxc3 16. c6 {This intermezzo is the key
that forces Black to play with an isolated pawn on d5.} Bxc6 17. Qxc3 Rc8 18. Qb3
{with nice positional edge.}) 14. Bf5 g6 15. Bh3 Nh5 {This happened in Sakaev,
K (2665)-Riazantsev, A (2556) Sochi 2004 and now it seems like White had an
interesting possibility to undermine Black pawn structure with:} 16. Bxe7 $146
Qxe7 17. b3 {It is crucial to get this move in before Black can support his
c-pawn with b5. In case of exchange on b3, he gets a permanent pressure
against d5, while also keeping an option for minority attack with a4-a5.} Rac8
18. bxc4 dxc4 {The pawn structure has become double-edged, but White gets a
better game with:} 19. Qa4 $1 Bc6 20. Qb4) 11. Rd1 c4 (11... Nbd7 12. O-O {
is covered through 10...Nbd7} ({while a well-known} 12. Ba6 {looks very
interesting for White, as well, in the view of possible pressure against
d5-pawn.})) 12. Bb1 {When the white queen is on c2, the bishop does not have that
option, but it makes a lot of sense to create the battery with queen first, if
possible.} a6 ({Another line is:} 12... Re8 13. O-O a6 14. Ne5 {White starts
the typical kingside attack with f4, Rf3-h3, etc.} b5 15. Qc2 Ne4 {This is
necessary to relieve some pressure off black position. However, White keeps
strong attacking chances with:} 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. f3 Nf6 {Farago,I (2486)
-Skembris, S (2475) Bratto 2000 and now:} 18. g4 $1 g6 19. Qg2 Nbd7 20. f4 $1 {
and Black is in a difficult spot.}) 13. Qc2 g6 14. h4 $5 {A surprising
approach, which worked very well in the game,} ({but I would rather prefer a
bit more conservative} 14. O-O Nbd7 15. Ne5 {with promising play, like in the
12...Re8 line.}) 14... Bc8 $2 (14... Ne4 {was a much better response for Black.
}) 15. Ne5 {and white attack was very powerful in Fier, A (2595)-Koziak, V (2479)
Marrakesh 2016.} *

